  <textList name="TEXT_CREW_TALK_ENGI_TWINS" ignoreUnique="true">
    <text> You overhear the two engi brothers arguing about something.
      "Unorthodox colors and inelegant gameboard = disposable." "Disregard conclusion. Colors contain context of terrestrial origins giving significance => similar activities."
      The first  brother makes an irritated looking gesture and says "you malfunction."
    </text>
    <text>The twins are arguing again. Remington is shouting. "SO F1--->HELP ME IF YOU THROW OUT MY GRAPHICS DRIVE AGAIN I WILL-"
      his voice cuts off suddenly. A small automated voice plays: "system error, please contact customer support." Mossberg sighs, calms themselves, and starts helping repair their brother.
    </text>
    <text>You run into the twins at the cafeteria. Remington looks extremely nervous as he slowly approaches....the microwave?! His brother quickly grabs him and pulls him away from it. "Its league > your league. Don't embarass yourself in front of her brother. You would achieve >= results calculating the square root of pie." Mossberg explains sternly to his brother. You start hiding the microwave from the twins.</text>
    <text>While checking in on the twins you find a video one of them was recording on their terminal.

      You hear one of the twins imitating a human voice you have never heard before,"Hi, I'm Mossberg and welcome to jackass!!" The twin then proceeded to throw itself out the airlock with what appears to be a life support tube tied around its waist, but forgot to tie the other end to anything! The video cuts abruptly after hearing Winchester yelling "Mossberg get idiot brother back here right damn now!!"
    </text>
    <text>You overhear the twin brothers laughing together about a joke you don't quite understand. But it is nice to see them enjoying themselves.</text>
    <text>You find the two Engi brothers at the cafeteria. They are playing a word game together where they have a conversation and start each sentence with the next letter in the human alphabet, and go back and forth with this game to get the other crew members to laugh. "Attention Remington, you are a potato-battery!" Mossberg says with a chuckle. "Be reasonable Mossberg, you haven't even seen a potato before." Remington responds back. "Clearly, you haven't seen my image folder on my terminal." Mossberg shoots back. "Disgusting, that is all I have to say." Remington says, concluding the game and agreeing that Mossberg wins this round. Their score is 453,752 - 462, 319.
    </text>
    <text>You find the two Engi brothers looking over a diagram of an Engi. They appear to be discussing how to most efficiently destroy them, or forcefully seperate an individual Engi from the Harmony.</text>


  </textList>

  <textList name="TEXT_CREW_TALK_ENGI_TWINS_COLLECTION" >
    <text>You browse Remington's boardgame collection. One of them catches your eye today, it is a game called THE KING IN CYAN. It depicts a robed humanoid figure in a bright cyan colored cloak standing over a ritual circle, perhaps some type of diety? You try to read the instruction manual, but it is 20 pages long, and you change your mind.</text>
    <text>You browse Remington's boardgame collection. One of them catches your eye today, it is a game called THEOCRACY. It involves rolling dice to move pieces around a board and claim different beacons, then gather "scrap leases" from other players that land on your beacons. The goal is to bankrupt the other players and take control of the government.</text>
    <text>You browse Remington's boardgame collection. One of them catches your eye today, it is a game called HUNGRY HUNGRY LANIUS. The game board is surrounded by four mechanical, colorful, plastic Lanius heads operated by levers on the backs of their head.

      When the lever is pressed, the Lanius opens its mouth and extends its head forwards on a telescopic neck. When the lever is released, the head comes down and retracts.

      Colored plastic ship hulls are dispensed into the board by each player, and the players repeatedly press the lever on their Lanius in order to have it "eat" the hulls, which travel down from under the Lanius into a small scoring area for each player. Once all hulls have been eaten, the player who has collected the most is the winner.
    </text>
    <text>You browse Remington's boardgame collection. One of them catches your eye today, it is a game called SPECULATE SOMEONE?: MANTIS EDITION. It has functionally the same ruleset as the boardgame SPECULATE SOMEONE? but it only has 24 characters and 1 race: the Mantis. You assume this is a simplified version for the Mantis to play. </text>
    <text>You browse Mossberg's comic collection. One of them catches your eye today, it is a comic called DEATH TO XENOS: THE CRUSADE. It is a crudely drawn comic book spreading Rebel propoganda about how bad the other alien species' continued existance is for the Rebel faction. You ask Mossberg about it, he says he keeps it "ironically" because it is so outlandish it becomes humorous.</text>
    <text>You browse Remington's boardgame collection. One of them catches your eye today, it is a game called SPECULATE SOMEONE?. Each player starts the game with a board that includes cartoon images of 336 people, 24 for each race. Each player selects a card of their choice from a separate pile of cards containing the same 336 images.
      The objective of the game is to be the first to determine which card one's opponent has selected.

      Players alternate asking various yes or no questions to eliminate candidates, such as:

      "Does your person wear a hat?"
      "Does your person have claws?"
      "Does your person have a body made of physical matter?"
      "Does your person have a free will?"
      The player will then eliminate candidates (based on the opponent's response) by flipping those images down until only one is left. According to the rules, it is not a legal question to ask what the other player's race is.
    </text>
    <text>You browse Mossberg's comic collection. One of them catches your eye today, it is a comic called BattleSickle: 80k. It depicts Mantis in gigantic power armor suits, fighting against the evil forces of the Engi Elders. </text>
    <text>You browse Mossberg's comic collection. One of them catches your eye today, it is a comic called Avaliman. It depicts a human dressed up as a bird that fights crime after their grandparents were killed. They fight crime and place super criminals in "Federation Asylum". </text>
  </textList>

